README.md
     1вҶ’# dotenv [![NPM version](https://img.shields.io/npm/v/dotenv.svg?style=flat-square)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dotenv) [![downloads](https://img.shields.io/npm/dw/dotenv)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dotenv)
     5вҶ’Dotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into [`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env). Storing configuration in the environment separate from code is based on [The Twelve-Factor App](https://12factor.net/config) methodology.
     6вҶ’
     7вҶ’[Watch the tutorial](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtkZR0NFd1g)
     8вҶ’
     9вҶ’&nbsp;
    10вҶ’
    11вҶ’## Usage
    13вҶ’Install it.
    14вҶ’
    15вҶ’```sh
    16вҶ’npm install dotenv --save
    17вҶ’```
    18вҶ’
    19вҶ’Create a `.env` file in the root of your project:
    20вҶ’
    21вҶ’```ini
    22вҶ’# .env
    23вҶ’S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    24вҶ’SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    25вҶ’```
    26вҶ’
    27вҶ’And as early as possible in your application, import and configure dotenv:
    28вҶ’
    29вҶ’```javascript
    30вҶ’require('dotenv').config() // or import 'dotenv/config' if you're using ES6
    31вҶ’...
    32вҶ’console.log(process.env) // remove this after you've confirmed it is working
    33вҶ’```
    34вҶ’
    35вҶ’That's it. `process.env` now has the keys and values you defined in your `.env` file:
    36вҶ’
    37вҶ’&nbsp;
    38вҶ’
    39вҶ’## Advanced
    43вҶ’Import with [ES6](#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import):
    44вҶ’
    45вҶ’```javascript
    46вҶ’import 'dotenv/config'
    47вҶ’```
    48вҶ’
    49вҶ’ES6 import if you need to set config options:
    50вҶ’
    51вҶ’```javascript
    52вҶ’import dotenv from 'dotenv'
    53вҶ’dotenv.config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
    54вҶ’```
    55вҶ’
    56вҶ’</details>
    57вҶ’<details><summary>bun</summary><br>
    58вҶ’
    59вҶ’```sh
    60вҶ’bun add dotenv
    61вҶ’```
    62вҶ’
    63вҶ’</details>
    64вҶ’<details><summary>yarn</summary><br>
    65вҶ’
    66вҶ’```sh
    67вҶ’yarn add dotenv
    68вҶ’```
    69вҶ’
    70вҶ’</details>
    71вҶ’<details><summary>pnpm</summary><br>
    72вҶ’
    73вҶ’```sh
    74вҶ’pnpm add dotenv
    75вҶ’```
    76вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   319вҶ’## Agents
   323вҶ’> Software is changing, and dotenv must change with itвҖ”that is why I built [agentic secret storage (AS2)](https://dotenvx.com/as2). Agents run code without humans at terminals, so plaintext `.env` files are the wrong primitive.
   324вҶ’>
   325вҶ’> AS2 is built for autonomous software: encrypted by default, zero console access, and cryptographyвҖ‘first delivery that keeps operators out of the loop.
   326вҶ’>
   327вҶ’> It is backed by [Vestauth](https://github.com/vestauth/vestauth), the trusted, pioneering auth layer for agentsвҖ”giving each agent a cryptographic identity so requests are signed with private keys and verified with public keys. No shared secrets to leak.
   328вҶ’>
   329вҶ’> It's what I'm using now. - [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   330вҶ’
   331вҶ’### Quickstart
   333вҶ’Install vestauth and initialize your agent.
   334вҶ’
   335вҶ’```bash
   336вҶ’npm i -g vestauth
   337вҶ’
   338вҶ’vestauth agent init
   339вҶ’```
   340вҶ’
   341вҶ’Your agent `set`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   342вҶ’
   343вҶ’```bash
   344вҶ’vestauth agent curl -X POST https://as2.dotenvx.com/set -d '{"KEY":"value"}'
   345вҶ’```
   346вҶ’
   347вҶ’And your agent `get`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   348вҶ’
   349вҶ’```bash
   350вҶ’vestauth agent curl "https://as2.dotenvx.com/get?key=KEY"
   351вҶ’```
   352вҶ’
   353вҶ’That's it! This new primitive unlocks secrets access for agents without human-in-the-loop, oauth flows, or API keys. It's the future for agents.
   354вҶ’
   355вҶ’&nbsp;
   356вҶ’
   357вҶ’## FAQ
   361вҶ’No.
   362вҶ’
   363вҶ’Unless you encrypt it with [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx). Then we recommend you do.
   364вҶ’
   365вҶ’</details>
   366вҶ’<details><summary>What about variable expansion?</summary><br/>
   367вҶ’
   368вҶ’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx).
   369вҶ’
   370вҶ’</details>
   371вҶ’<details><summary>Should I have multiple `.env` files?</summary><br/>
   372вҶ’
   373вҶ’We recommend creating one `.env` file per environment. Use `.env` for local/development, `.env.production` for production and so on. This still follows the twelve factor principles as each is attributed individually to its own environment. Avoid custom set ups that work in inheritance somehow (`.env.production` inherits values form `.env` for example). It is better to duplicate values if necessary across each `.env.environment` file.
   374вҶ’
   375вҶ’> In a twelve-factor app, env vars are granular controls, each fully orthogonal to other env vars. They are never grouped together as вҖңenvironmentsвҖқ, but instead are independently managed for each deploy. This is a model that scales up smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys over its lifetime.
   376вҶ’>
   377вҶ’> вҖ“ [The Twelve-Factor App](http://12factor.net/config)
   378вҶ’
   379вҶ’Additionally, we recommend using [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to encrypt and manage these.
   380вҶ’
   381вҶ’</details>
   382вҶ’
   383вҶ’<details><summary>How do I use dotenv with `import`?</summary><br/>
   384вҶ’
   385вҶ’Simply..
   386вҶ’
   387вҶ’```javascript
   388вҶ’// index.mjs (ESM)
   389вҶ’import 'dotenv/config' // see https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import
   390вҶ’import express from 'express'
   391вҶ’```
   392вҶ’
   393вҶ’A little background..
   394вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   579вҶ’## Docs
   581вҶ’Dotenv exposes four functions:
   582вҶ’
   583вҶ’* `config`
   584вҶ’* `parse`
   585вҶ’* `populate`
   586вҶ’
   587вҶ’### Config
   589вҶ’`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590вҶ’[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591вҶ’and return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592вҶ’
   593вҶ’```js
   594вҶ’const result = dotenv.config()
   595вҶ’
   596вҶ’if (result.error) {
   597вҶ’  throw result.error
   598вҶ’}
   599вҶ’
   600вҶ’console.log(result.parsed)
   601вҶ’```
   602вҶ’
   603вҶ’You can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604вҶ’
   605вҶ’#### Options
   607вҶ’##### path
   609вҶ’Default: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610вҶ’
   611вҶ’Specify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612вҶ’
   613вҶ’```js
   614вҶ’require('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615вҶ’```
   616вҶ’
   617вҶ’By default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618вҶ’
   619вҶ’Pass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620вҶ’
   621вҶ’```js  
   622вҶ’require('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623вҶ’```
   624вҶ’
   625вҶ’##### quiet
   627вҶ’Default: `false`
   628вҶ’
   629вҶ’Suppress runtime logging message.
   630вҶ’
   631вҶ’```js
   632вҶ’// index.js
   633вҶ’require('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634вҶ’console.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635вҶ’```
   636вҶ’
   637вҶ’```ini
   638вҶ’# .env
   639вҶ’HELLO=World
   640вҶ’```
   641вҶ’
   642вҶ’```sh
   643вҶ’$ node index.js
   644вҶ’[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645вҶ’Hello World
   646вҶ’```
   647вҶ’
   648вҶ’##### encoding
   650вҶ’Default: `utf8`
   651вҶ’
   652вҶ’Specify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653вҶ’
   654вҶ’```js
   655вҶ’require('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656вҶ’```
   657вҶ’
   658вҶ’##### debug
   660вҶ’Default: `false`
   661вҶ’
   662вҶ’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663вҶ’
   664вҶ’```js
   665вҶ’require('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666вҶ’```
   667вҶ’
   668вҶ’##### override
   670вҶ’Default: `false`
   671вҶ’
   672вҶ’Override any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673вҶ’
   674вҶ’```js
   675вҶ’require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676вҶ’```
   677вҶ’
   678вҶ’##### processEnv
   680вҶ’Default: `process.env`
   681вҶ’
   682вҶ’Specify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683вҶ’
   684вҶ’```js
   685вҶ’const myObject = {}
   686вҶ’require('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687вҶ’
   688вҶ’console.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689вҶ’console.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690вҶ’```
   691вҶ’
   692вҶ’### Parse
   694вҶ’The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695вҶ’variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696вҶ’an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697вҶ’
   698вҶ’```js
   699вҶ’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700вҶ’const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701вҶ’const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702вҶ’console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703вҶ’```
   704вҶ’
   705вҶ’#### Options
   707вҶ’##### debug
   709вҶ’Default: `false`
   710вҶ’
   711вҶ’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712вҶ’
   713вҶ’```js
   714вҶ’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715вҶ’const buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716вҶ’const opt = { debug: true }
   717вҶ’const config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718вҶ’// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719вҶ’```
   720вҶ’
   721вҶ’### Populate
   723вҶ’The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724вҶ’
   725вҶ’For example, customizing the source:
   726вҶ’
   727вҶ’```js
   728вҶ’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729вҶ’const parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730вҶ’
   731вҶ’dotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732вҶ’
   733вҶ’console.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734вҶ’```
   735вҶ’
   736вҶ’For example, customizing the source AND target:
   737вҶ’
   738вҶ’```js
   739вҶ’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740вҶ’const parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741вҶ’const target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742вҶ’
   743вҶ’dotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744вҶ’
   745вҶ’console.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746вҶ’```
   747вҶ’
   748вҶ’#### options
   750вҶ’##### Debug
   752вҶ’Default: `false`
   753вҶ’
   754вҶ’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755вҶ’
   756вҶ’##### override
   758вҶ’Default: `false`
   759вҶ’
   760вҶ’Override any environment variables that have already been set.
   761вҶ’
   762вҶ’&nbsp;
   763вҶ’
